line_1: If I should see a black-bird, or a thrush,
line_2: Sit on her nest within the hawthorn bush,

line_1: The bulfinch, linnet, nightingale, and thrush;
line_2: Trills in each tree, and dies in every bush.

line_1: The blackbird, linnet, finch, and thrush,
line_2: Pour out their songs from every bush;

line_1: And listen to the sweet thick-warbling thrush,
line_2: Here let me stop beneath this spreading bush,

line_1: In the next orchat liv'd a friendly thrush,
line_2: All in a garden, on a currant-bush,

line_1: The warbling blackbird and the thrush,
line_2: See glist'ning dew drops on the bush,

line_1: Stopt in her song perchance the starting thrush
line_2: Shook a white shower from the black-thorn bush,

line_1: Hark how the gaudy Goldfinch, and the Thrush,
line_2: With tuneful Warblings fill that Bramble-Bush!
